passages.text: Deutsche Bank Research
US GDP revised up; mapping US asset ownership; step- up in US term premium
US GDP revised up & jobless claims drop back a bit. Australia needs more flats, fewer fences...

USA: GDP (Q2): Revised up 0.3pps to \(3.3\%\) saar in 2nd estimate. USA: Pending home sales (Jul): Down \(0.4\%\) mom, below mkt. USA: Kansas City Fed manufacturing (Aug): Unchanged at 1pt, at mkt. USA: Initial jobless claims (Aug 23): At \(229k\) , below mkt. EMU: ECB (Jul): Most members viewed inf outlook risks as broadly balanced. EMU: Consumer confidence (Aug): Confirmed at - 15.5pts. AUS: Private capital expenditure (Q2): Up \(0.2\%\) mom, below mkt. NZL: ANZ business confidence (Aug): Up 1.9pts to 49.7. NZL: Filled jobs (Jul): Up \(0.2\%\) mom.
US equities were stronger Thursday, S&P up \(0.3\%\) , fresh record high. US10yr yields down 3bps to \(4.20\%\) .

US GDP revised up by 0.3ppts to \(3.3\%\) annualized in Q2, consensus expected a 0.1ppt upward revision. Very small downward revisions (at 2 decimal places) to core PCE deflator for the quarter (now \(2.47\%\) qoq versus 2.54%qoq), so still at \(2.5\%\) annualized.
US jobless claims drop back a bit. Initial claims down 5k to \(229k\) in latest week, continuing claims down 7k to 1954k. Still no signs here pointing to any broad- based deterioration.

Kansas City Fed manufacturing steady at 1pt in August, in line with consensus. Mixed bag across the full suite of regional US manufacturing indices for August: two fell, two rose and one (Kansas) was steady.

DB's Al tool interpreted the July ECB meeting minutes as dovish, a shift from leaning hawkish in June. Michal Kirker concludes that, for now at least, the ECB do not seem troubled by EUR's appreciation as they see it as mainly driven by endogenous factors, so the inflationary impact will be limited. But the dispersion of views on the risks around the inflation outlook suggest the ECB is perhaps more uncertain about the future than the press conference portrayed. DB's base case remains that ECB is at its terminal rate, though there is some risk of further easing.

Australia CAPEX missed: Up \(0.2\%\) qoq in Q2, consensus at \(0.8\%\) qoq. Coupled with construction work done, which was stronger but on a mining project coming to completion, investment partials for Q2 lean a bit weaker against our pick for a \(0.5\%\) qoq GDP print.

NZ filled jobs up \(0.2\%\) mom in July. Early signal pointing to some recovery from the drop in employment in Q2. RBNZ still on track to cut 50bps (DB expects 25bps at October and November meetings).

Mapping US asset ownership. Adjusting official statistics on foreign ownership for the well- known measurement problems around ultimate beneficial ownership, Soha Rizkallah finds that the Scandinavian economies, Singapore, Switzerland, Japan and Canada stand out as having the largest exposures to US assets exceeding \(50\%\) of domestic output. Canada's exposure stands out the most, with more than two thirds of foreign assets allocated to the US. Japan's is most heavily skewed towards fixed income. EM ownership of US assets is generally smaller.

Francis Yared's US term premium proxy has risen by \(\sim 60\) bps since he argued for a structural increase 3 years ago. And from a tactical perspective, the coming two months tend favourable for a further step- up. The main risks come from (1) US tariff revenues exceeding expectations enough to generate a material fiscal tightening, (2) Al exerting significant disinflationary pressures, and (3) OPEC+'s attempt to regain market share resulting in a significant decline in oil prices comparable to what was observed in 2014.

US equities are strong, but are they exceptionally strong? Tim Baker notes the return of US equities to highs in recent months (S&P fresh record high Thursday) has fuelled a resurgence of the US exceptionalism story. But other markets are doing well too, and when they keep pace with US equities, USD tends to soften. Cheaper equity markets on a valuation basis (EM, Europe) have outperformed, and while the TIC data indicate huge buying of US equities (which helping the US exceptionalism theme) an adjusted version of the data look a lot softer. Japan seems to edging towards European bonds, at some cost to US flows. All up, the relative appeal of US assets has declined at least a little.

DB's nowcast for German GDP growth is tracking at a good \(+0.2\%\) qoq for Q3, above consensus at \(0.1\%\) qoq, but the downward revision to Q2 growth (now - \(0.3\%\) qoq) will weigh n annual growth, Still, Marc Schattenberg remains optimistic about 2026 when clearly expansive fiscal policy should support growth of \(2\%\) in 2026, \(1.5\%\) in 2027.

Even after adjusting for inflation, every \(1\) bn spent in residential construction in Australia is delivering about 300 fewer dwellings than it did in 2019. Productivity is part of the problem. But the main driver is the type of dwellings currently being built. History - and evidence from Germany - suggests the Australian Government's target of building 1.2mn dwellings in 5 years will be more achievable if construction tilts significantly in favour of attached dwellings (apartments) rather than stand- alone houses. And if the Government has any chance of achieving its target, it might need to do so in a hurry.

Macroeconomic fluctuations often account for most of the risks associated with exposures to instruments that promise to pay fixed or variable interest rates. For an investor who is long fixed- rate instruments (thus receiving these cash flows), increases in interest rates naturally lift the discount factors applied to the expected cash flows and thus cause a loss. The longer the maturity of a certain cash flow and the higher the move in the discount factor, the higher will be the loss. Upside surprises in inflation, fiscal funding needs, and FX depreciation rates are among the most common adverse macroeconomic shocks to receivers. But counterparty exposure, issuer creditworthiness, client segmentation, regulation (including changes in assets holding limits for different types of investors), changes in tax policies, currency convertibility (which may constrain currency conversion, repatriation of profits and/or liquidation of positions), and settlement issues related to local clearing houses are also important risk factors. The sensitivity of fixed- income instruments to macroeconomic shocks may be mitigated by indexing the contracted cash flows to inflation, to FX depreciation, or to specified interest rates - these are common in emerging markets. The index fixings may - by construction - lag or mis- measure the actual move in the underlying variables they are intended to track. The choice of the proper fixing (or metric) is particularly important in swaps markets, where floating coupon rates (i.e., coupons indexed to a typically short- dated interest rate reference index) are exchanged for fixed coupons. Funding in a currency that differs from the currency in which coupons are denominated carries FX risk.
